James Sousa: Determining Values Using Perpendicular Bisectors

Guidance

A perpendicular bisector is a line that intersects a line segment at its midpoint and is perpendicular to that line

segment, as shown in the construction below.

One important property related to perpendicular bisectors is that if a point is on the perpendicular bisector of a

segment, then it is equidistant from the endpoints of the segment. This is called the Perpendicular Bisector

Theorem.

←→

If CD⊥ AB and AD = DB, then AC =CB.

In addition to the Perpendicular Bisector Theorem, the converse is also true.

